  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent and report money laundering. These typically include:\n\n1. Know Your Customer (KYC) requirements\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n\n2. Reporting requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Maintaining transaction records\n\n3. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) compliance programs\n- Developing internal policies and procedures\n- Training employees\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n\n4. Legal frameworks\n- Compliance with Bank Secrecy Act\n- Following Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Adhering to international anti-money laundering regulations\n\n5. Due diligence\n- Assessing customer risk levels\n- Investigating unusual transaction patterns\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring\n\nFailure to meet these obligations can result in significant legal penalties, including:\n- Substantial financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n\nSpecific requirements can vary by jurisdiction, but most developed countries have robust anti-money laundering legal frameworks for financial institutions.",
